    <p>At the end of an A&amp;P module, the recurring student question is straightforward: how does this translate into my OT essays and case studies? The answer is consistent across practice areas. Understanding parietal lobe function enables a student to justify the selection of a neglect assessment tool in a stroke case study, because the assessment targets the clinical consequence of parietal damage. Understanding the myelination timeline enables a student to interpret a Sensory Profile 2 score in a paediatric OT assignment, because the score only has clinical meaning relative to the child's developmental stage. Understanding Zone II flexor tendon anatomy enables a student to explain why early controlled mobilisation is the OT protocol of choice post-surgery, because the anatomy explains the clinical risk. The A&amp;P content on this page is not background reading. Each section maps to a specific OT assignment context described in the supplementary content below.</p>
